ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: Visit name
Notes: e.g., Baseline, 6-Month Follow Up, Year 2, Daily

ElementDescription: Considering only your own "feeling best" rhythm, at what time would you get up if you were entirely free to plan your day?
Considering only your own "feeling best" rhythm, at what time would you go to bed if you were entirely free to plan your evening?
Assuming normal circumstances, how easy do you find getting up in the morning?
Notes: 1 = Very easy; 2 = Fairly easy; 3 = Slightly easy; 4 = Not at all easy

ElementDescription: How alert do you feel during the first half hour after having awakened in the morning?
Notes: 1 = Very alert; 2 = Fairly alert; 3 = Slightly alert; 4 = Not at all alert

ElementDescription: During the first half hour after having awakened in the morning, how tired do you feel?
Notes: 1 = Very refreshed; 2 = Fairly refreshed; 3 = Fairly tired; 4 = Very tried

ElementDescription: You have decided to engage in some physical exercise. A friend suggests that you do this one hour twice a week and the best time for him is 7:00- 8:00 a.m. Bearing in mind nothing but your own "feeling best" rhythm, how do you think you would perform?
Notes: 1 = Would be in good form; 2 = Would be in a reasonable form; 3 = Would find it difficult; 4 = Would find it very difficult

ElementDescription: At what time in the evening do you feel tired and, as a result, in need of sleep?

You wish to be at your peak performance for a test which you know is going to be mentally exhausting and lasting two hours. You are entirely free to plan your day, and considering only your own "feeling best" rhythm, which ONE of the four testing times would you choose?
One hears about "morning" and "evening" types of people. Which ONE of these types do you consider yourself to be?
Notes: 1 = Definitely a morning type; 2 = More a morning type than an evening type; 3 = More an evening type than a moring type; 4 = Definitely an evening type

ElementDescription: When would you prefer to rise (provided you have a full day's work-- 8 hours) if you were totally free to arrange your time?
If you always had to rise at 6:00 a.m., what do you think it would be like?
Notes: 1 = Easy and not unpleasant; 2 = A little unpleasant but no great problem; 3 = Rather difficult and unpleasant; 4 = Very difficult an unpleasant

ElementDescription: How long a time does it usually take before you "recover your senses" in the morning after rising from a night's sleep?
Notes: 1 = 0-10 minutes; 2 = 11-20 minutes; 3 = 21-40 minutes; 4 = More than 40 minutes

ElementDescription: Please indicate to what extent you are a morning or evening active individual.
Notes: 1 = Pronounced morning active (morning alert and evening tired); 2 = To some extent, morning active; 3 = To some extent, evening active; 4 = Pronounced evening active (morning tired and evening alert)

ElementDescription: Subject's Primary Language
date ended (today's date if still in progress)
Response Type
Notes: 0 = IP Address; 1 = Survey Preview; 2 = Survey Test; 4 = Imported; 8 = Spam; 9 = Survey Preview Spam; 12 = Imported Spam; 16 = Offline; 17 = Offline Survey Preview; 32 = EX; 40 = EX Spam; 48 = EX Offline;

ElementDescription: Progress
Trial 1 duration of task, seconds
Checks if completed
Notes: 0=No; 1=Yes; 2=Yes, lost; 3=Unverified; -1= Not applicable

ElementDescription: Date record updated
External Data Reference
Morningness/Eveningness score
Notes: 1=Evening Type 22 and less; 2=Intermediate Type 23-43; 3=Morning Type 44 and above

ElementDescription: Morningness/Eveningness score Reversed
Notes: 1=Morning type 24 and less; 2= Intermediate type 25-45; 3= Evening type 46 and above

ElementDescription: At what time of the day do you think you reach your ''feeling best'' peak?
Notes: 1 = 10pm - 5am; 2 = 5pm - 10pm; 3 = 10am - 5pm; 4 = 8am - 10am; 5 = 5am - 8am; 6 = No answer

ElementDescription: Respondent
Notes: NA=Not Applicable

ElementDescription: Morning activation deficit score based off items comp3, comp4, compt6, comp12
Notes: 1= Severe morning activation deficits; 12= Less morning activation deficits

ElementDescription: Date and Time EMA survey was completed
Morningness/Eveningness Total score (actual)
Notes: Sum of [(6 - Comp1), (6 - Comp2), Comp3, Comp4, Comp5, (5 - Comp6), (6 - Comp7), (5 - Comp8), (5 - Comp9), (5 - Comp10), Comp11, (5 - Comp12), (5 - Comp13)]; Evening Type 22 and less; Intermediate Type 23-43; Morning Type 44 and above
